            "content": "# Request-Scoped Caching Guide\n\nThis guide explains how to use Memento's scoped caching feature, which is particularly useful for web applications.\n\n## The Problem\n\nConsider a typical web request that calls multiple functions:\n\n```clojure\n(defn handle-request [request]\n  (let [user (get-user (:user-id request))\n        orders (get-user-orders (:user-id request))\n        prefs (get-user-preferences (:user-id request))]\n    (render-page user orders prefs)))\n```\n\nWith traditional memoization, you have two problems:\n\n1. **Stale data**: Request A might see data cached by Request B from seconds ago\n2. **Memory leaks**: Caches grow unbounded across requests\n\nYou want caching that:\n- Starts **fresh** for each request\n- Is **discarded** when the request ends\n- Can still **consult** long-term caches for data\n\n## The Solution: `with-caches`\n\nMemento's `with-caches` macro temporarily replaces caches for tagged functions:\n\n```clojure\n(require '[memento.core :as m]\n         '[memento.config :as mc])\n\n;; Tag functions that should have request-scoped caching\n(m/defmemo get-user\n  {mc/tags [:request]}\n  [user-id]\n  (db/fetch-user user-id))\n\n(m/defmemo get-user-orders\n  {mc/tags [:request]}\n  [user-id]\n  (db/fetch-orders user-id))\n\n;; In your request handling\n(m/with-caches :request\n  (constantly (m/create {}))  ; Factory that creates a fresh empty cache\n  (handle-request request))\n```\n\nInside `with-caches`:\n- All `:request`-tagged functions use a fresh cache\n- The cache is discarded when the block exits\n- Functions called with the same arguments within the block hit the cache\n\n## Ring Middleware Pattern\n\nWrap your Ring handler to provide request-scoped caching:\n\n```clojure\n(defn wrap-request-cache [handler]\n  (fn [request]\n    (m/with-caches :request\n      (constantly (m/create {}))\n      (handler request))))\n\n;; Apply to your app\n(def app\n  (-> handler\n      wrap-request-cache\n      wrap-params\n      wrap-session))\n```\n\nNow all `:request`-tagged cached functions automatically get a fresh cache per request.\n\n## Consulting Long-Term Caches\n\nOften you want request-scoped caching but also want to benefit from a long-term cache. Use `m/consulting`:\n\n```clojure\n;; Long-term cache for users (1 hour TTL)\n(def user-cache (m/create {mc/ttl [1 :h] mc/size< 10000}))\n\n(m/defmemo get-user\n  {mc/tags [:request]}\n  [user-id]\n  (db/fetch-user user-id))\n\n;; Bind to the long-term cache by default\n(m/bind #'get-user {} user-cache)\n\n;; Middleware that consults the long-term cache\n(defn wrap-request-cache [handler]\n  (fn [request]\n    (m/with-caches :request\n      (fn [existing-cache]\n        ;; Create a request cache that CONSULTS the long-term cache\n        (m/create (m/consulting {} existing-cache)))\n      (handler request))))\n```\n\nWith `consulting`:\n- Cache **hits** check request cache first, then long-term cache\n- Cache **misses** fetch data and store in request cache only\n- Long-term cache is **not modified** by request-scoped operations\n\nThis is the recommended pattern for most web applications.\n\n## Multiple Scope Tags\n\nYou can have multiple scope levels:\n\n```clojure\n(m/defmemo get-user\n  {mc/tags [:request :user]}  ; Participates in both scopes\n  [user-id]\n  (db/fetch-user user-id))\n\n;; Outer scope for long-running operations\n(m/with-caches :user\n  (constantly (m/create {mc/ttl [5 :m]}))\n  \n  ;; Inner scope for each request\n  (m/with-caches :request\n    (constantly (m/create {}))\n    (handle-request request)))\n```\n\n## Permanently Updating Caches\n\nIf you need to permanently change the cache for all tagged functions (not just within a scope), use `update-tag-caches!`:\n\n```clojure\n;; Replace ALL :request-tagged caches with new empty caches\n(m/update-tag-caches! :request (constantly (m/create {})))\n```\n\nThis is useful for:\n- Clearing all caches of a certain type\n- Replacing caches during application reconfiguration\n- Testing\n\n## Inspecting Tagged Functions\n\n### List Functions by Tag\n\n```clojure\n;; Get all mount points tagged with :request\n(m/mounts-by-tag :request)\n;; => #{#memento.mount.TaggedMountPoint{...} ...}\n\n;; Get the caches being used\n(m/caches-by-tag :request)\n;; => [#memento.caffeine.CaffeineCache{...} ...]\n```\n\n### Get Tags for a Function\n\n```clojure\n(m/tags get-user)\n;; => [:request :user]\n```\n\n## How `with-caches` Works\n\n1. When entering the block, a new cache is created via your factory function\n2. The existing cache is passed to your factory (so you can wrap it)\n3. A thread-local binding is set up mapping the tag to the new cache\n4. Tagged functions check this binding and use the scoped cache\n5. When the block exits, the binding is removed and the cache can be GCed\n\nThis means:\n- Scoped caches are thread-local (safe for concurrent requests)\n- Nested `with-caches` blocks work correctly\n- No manual cleanup needed\n\n## Comparison of Multi-Cache Types\n\nWhen combining request-scoped and long-term caches, you have three options:\n\n| Type | Use Case | After Miss |\n|------|----------|------------|\n| `m/consulting` | Request cache in front of long-term | Entry in request cache only |\n| `m/tiered` | Local cache in front of external (Redis) | Entry in both caches |\n| `m/daisy` | Pre-loaded cache with fallback | Entry in upstream only |\n\n### `consulting` (Most Common for Request Scoping)\n\n```clojure\n(m/consulting {} long-term-cache)\n```\n\n- Check request cache, then long-term cache\n- Only request cache is updated\n- Long-term cache is read-only from request's perspective\n\n### `tiered`\n\n```clojure\n(m/tiered {} long-term-cache)\n```\n\n- Check local, then upstream\n- Both caches get the entry\n- Use for local cache in front of slow external cache (Redis, etc.)\n\n### `daisy`\n\n```clojure\n(m/daisy pre-loaded-cache upstream-cache)\n```\n\n- Return from local if present, else hit upstream\n- Local is never updated\n- Use when local has pre-loaded/fixed data\n\n## Complete Example\n\n```clojure\n(ns myapp.cache\n  (:require [memento.core :as m]\n            [memento.config :as mc]))\n\n;; Long-term caches\n(def user-cache (m/create {mc/ttl [1 :h] mc/size< 10000}))\n(def product-cache (m/create {mc/ttl [5 :m] mc/size< 50000}))\n\n;; Cached functions\n(m/defmemo get-user\n  {mc/tags [:request :user]}\n  [user-id]\n  (db/fetch-user user-id))\n(m/bind #'get-user {} user-cache)\n\n(m/defmemo get-product\n  {mc/tags [:request]}\n  [product-id]\n  (db/fetch-product product-id))\n(m/bind #'get-product {} product-cache)\n\n;; Middleware\n(defn wrap-request-cache [handler]\n  (fn [request]\n    (m/with-caches :request\n      (fn [existing]\n        (m/create (m/consulting {} existing)))\n      (handler request))))\n\n;; Handler\n(defn handle-product-page [request]\n  (let [user (get-user (:user-id request))        ; Hits request cache, \n        product (get-product (:product-id request)) ; consults long-term\n        user-again (get-user (:user-id request))]   ; Hits request cache\n    (render-page user product)))\n```\n\nIn this example:\n- Each request gets a fresh cache\n- Repeated calls within a request hit the request cache\n- Long-term caches provide data but aren't modified\n- Caches are automatically cleaned up after each request\n",
