            "newString": "## Concurrency Considerations\n\n### Single Load Per Key\n\nIf multiple threads request the same uncached key simultaneously, only one actually calls the function. The others wait and receive the same result.\n\n### Invalidation During Load\n\nIf a key is invalidated while being loaded, the load is retried to ensure fresh data. The loading thread is interrupted when a tag is invalidated.\n\n### The Call Tree Problem\n\nThe hardest concurrency challenge with caching is **invalidating call trees** - cached functions that call other cached functions.\n\nConsider this scenario:\n\n```clojure\n(m/defmemo get-user-summary [user-id]    ; Calls get-user-details\n  (let [details (get-user-details user-id)]\n    (summarize details)))\n\n(m/defmemo get-user-details [user-id]    ; Lower-level cache\n  (db/fetch-user user-id))\n```\n\nWhen you invalidate both caches, there's a race condition:\n\n1. You invalidate `get-user-summary` for user 123\n2. Before you invalidate `get-user-details`, another thread calls `get-user-summary`\n3. That call misses, calls `get-user-details`, which still has **stale data**\n4. The stale data gets cached in the freshly-cleared `get-user-summary`\n5. You finally invalidate `get-user-details` - but `get-user-summary` now has stale data\n\n### Solutions\n\n#### Best: Shared Cache with Atomic Clear\n\nThe most robust solution is to back related functions with a **single shared cache** and clear it atomically:\n\n```clojure\n;; Create one cache for all user-related functions\n(def user-cache (m/create {mc/type mc/caffeine mc/size< 10000}))\n\n;; Bind multiple functions to the same cache\n(m/defmemo get-user-details [user-id]\n  (db/fetch-user user-id))\n\n(m/defmemo get-user-summary [user-id]\n  (summarize (get-user-details user-id)))\n\n(m/bind #'get-user-details {} user-cache)\n(m/bind #'get-user-summary {} user-cache)\n\n;; Clear the entire cache atomically - no race condition possible\n(m/memo-clear-cache! user-cache)\n```\n\nWhen you clear the shared cache, all entries for all functions are invalidated in one atomic operation. There's no window where one function has stale data while another is cleared.\n\nThis pattern works well when:\n- Functions are closely related (same entity type)\n- You often need to invalidate them together\n- You want a shared size limit across functions\n\n#### Good: Tag-Based Invalidation with Lockout\n\nWhen using tag-based invalidation (`memo-clear-tag!`), Memento uses locking mechanisms to coordinate invalidation across all tagged functions. This is a best-effort solution - it significantly reduces the window for race conditions but cannot eliminate them entirely in all edge cases.\n\n```clojure\n;; Tag-based invalidation coordinates across functions\n(m/memo-clear-tag! :user user-id)\n```\n\n#### Also Good: Request-Scoped Caching\n\nFor critical consistency, use request-scoped caching where each request gets a fresh cache. There's no stale data because every request starts empty.\n\nMost caching libraries don't address the call tree problem at all. Memento provides multiple strategies depending on your consistency requirements.\n\nSee [Internals](internals.md) for details on the lockout mechanism.",
            "oldString": "## Concurrency Considerations\n\n### Single Load Per Key\n\nIf multiple threads request the same uncached key simultaneously, only one actually calls the function. The others wait and receive the same result.\n\n### Invalidation During Load\n\nIf a key is invalidated while being loaded, the load is retried to ensure fresh data. The loading thread is interrupted when a tag is invalidated.\n\n### The Call Tree Problem\n\nThe hardest concurrency challenge with caching is **invalidating call trees** - cached functions that call other cached functions.\n\nConsider this scenario:\n\n```clojure\n(m/defmemo get-user-summary [user-id]    ; Calls get-user-details\n  (let [details (get-user-details user-id)]\n    (summarize details)))\n\n(m/defmemo get-user-details [user-id]    ; Lower-level cache\n  (db/fetch-user user-id))\n```\n\nWhen you invalidate both caches, there's a race condition:\n\n1. You invalidate `get-user-summary` for user 123\n2. Before you invalidate `get-user-details`, another thread calls `get-user-summary`\n3. That call misses, calls `get-user-details`, which still has **stale data**\n4. The stale data gets cached in the freshly-cleared `get-user-summary`\n5. You finally invalidate `get-user-details` - but `get-user-summary` now has stale data\n\n**Memento's approach**: When using tag-based invalidation (`memo-clear-tag!`), Memento uses locking mechanisms to coordinate invalidation across all tagged functions. This is a best-effort solution - it significantly reduces the window for race conditions but cannot eliminate them entirely in all edge cases.\n\n**Recommendations**:\n\n- Use `memo-clear-tag!` instead of multiple `memo-clear!` calls for related data\n- Use `memo-clear-tags!` when invalidating multiple tag+id pairs for better atomicity\n- For critical consistency, consider request-scoped caching where each request gets a fresh cache\n\nMost caching libraries don't address this problem at all. Memento's tag-based invalidation