            "oldString": "## Cache Configuration Options\n\nThese settings control the cache itself. Use vars from `memento.config` (aliased as `mc`).\n\n### `mc/type`\n\nCache implementation type.\n\n```clojure\n{mc/type mc/caffeine}  ; High-performance Caffeine cache\n{mc/type mc/none}      ; No-op cache, does not cache anything\n```\n\nIf you omit `mc/type`, the cache defaults to a no-op cache. This is useful for **scoped caching** where you want no caching outside of scopes, providing the cache only when entering a scope via `with-caches`.\n\nYou can also use scoped caching with a default cache - `with-caches` will replace it within the scope. See the [Scoped Caching Guide](scoped-caching.md) for both patterns.\n\n### `mc/size<`\n\nMaximum number of entries. Uses LRU (Least Recently Used) eviction.\n\n```clojure\n{mc/size< 1000}  ; Max 1000 entries\n```\n\n### `mc/ttl`\n\nTime-to-live. Entries expire after this duration since creation.\n\n```clojure\n{mc/ttl 60}       ; 60 seconds\n{mc/ttl [5 :m]}   ; 5 minutes\n{mc/ttl [2 :h]}   ; 2 hours\n{mc/ttl [1 :d]}   ; 1 day\n```\n\n**Time units:** `:ns` (nanoseconds), `:us` (microseconds), `:ms` (milliseconds), `:s` (seconds), `:m` (minutes), `:h` (hours), `:d` (days)\n\n### `mc/fade`\n\nAccess-based expiration. Entries expire after this duration since last access.\n\n```clojure\n{mc/fade [10 :m]}  ; Expire if not accessed for 10 minutes\n```\n\n### `mc/initial-capacity`\n\nHint for initial hash table size. Optional optimization.\n\n```clojure\n{mc/initial-capacity 256}\n```\n\n## Mount Configuration Options"
